# Learned Patterns: General

Auto-generated from 2 incidents in hippocampus.

## 1. ERROR: LLM reranking with 0.6 LLM weight caused false negatives — relevant query 'how does consolidation work in hippocampus' was rejected as irrelevant
ROOT CAUSE: LLM weight too high (0.6) and SemanticSimilarity was being modified by LLM scores. Local qwen2.5:7b gave low relevance scores (avg < 3) to relevant documents, pulling SemanticSimilarity below the rejection threshold
FIX: Reduced LLM weight to 0.4, kept cosine weight at 0.6. Stopped modifying SemanticSimilarity — only Composite is blended. Added safety: if avg LLM score < 2.0, discard all LLM scores
PREVENTION: Never modify SemanticSimilarity with external signals — it's the ground truth for rejection decisions. LLM reranking should only affect ordering (Composite), not absolute similarity thresholds
FILE: internal/app/recall_service.go

## 2. ERROR: panic: runtime error: index out of range [3] with length 3
CONTEXT: Running benchmark with spread heuristic, scored array had exactly 3 elements
ROOT CAUSE: Spread heuristic accessed scored[2] which is the 3rd element (index 2), but the check was len(scored) >= 3 which is correct. The actual panic was in a different code path where we accessed scored[3].
FIX: Changed scored[3] to scored[2] and added bounds check
PREVENTION: Always use len()-1 as max index, add bounds checks before array access
FILE: internal/app/recall_service.go

